      <div xml:id="NA55-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaiviṭai melivu āṟṟuvikkun tōḻi talaivaṟkuc (EV: talaimakaṟkuc) colliyatu. C1, G1+2: itu varaviṭai melivu āṟṟuvikkun tōḻikkut talaivi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante, who was encouraging [HER in her] weakness [until] the time of marriage, said to HIM. C1, G1+2: This is what SHE said to the confidante who was encouraging [HER in her] weakness [until] the time of marriage.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA55">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ōṅkumalai nāṭa voḻikaniṉ vāymai</l>
<l>            kāmputalai maṇanta kallatarc ciṟuneṟi</l>
<l>            yuṟupakai pēṇā tiraviṉ vantivaḷ</l>
<l>            poṟikiḷa rākam pullat tōḷcēr</l>
<l>            paṟukāṟ paṟavai yaḷavila moyttaliṟ </l>
<l>            kaṇkō ḷāka nōkkip paṇṭu</l>
<l>            miṉaiyai yōveṉa viṉaviṉaḷ yāyē</l>
<l>            yataṉetir collā ḷāki yallān</l>
<l>            teṉmuka nōkki yōḷē yaṉṉā</l>
<l>            yāṅkuṇarn tuykuvaḷ kolleṉa maṭutta </l>
<l>            cānta ñekiḻi kāṭṭi</l>
<l>            yīṅkā yiṉavā leṉṟiciṉ yāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">O man from a land of high mountains,</l>
<l rend="indent3">let your truthfulness stay behind.</l>
<l rend="indent2">Looking as if with a cluster of eyes<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṇ kōḷ āka</term>: this phrase referring to the way the mother looks might be interpreted at least in two ways, either as above (which would be literally: "looking so [her] eyes become a [whole] cluster") or, thinking of <term xml:lang="ta">kōḷ</term> as an epithet given to tigers: "looking, while [her] eyes turned murderous".</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">at the swarming of countless six-legged wing[ed ones]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṟukāl paṟavai</term>: this is undoubtedly a metaphor for bee. Is it an analogue to (or a translation of) Skt. <term xml:lang="sa">ṣaṭpada</term>-?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">having joined<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cērpu</term>: actually we would prefer the pey. p.a. <term xml:lang="ta">cērnta</term> here.</note> [her] shoulders</l>
<l rend="indent">when [you] came at night without regard for the enmity</l>
<l rend="indent2">there on the stony sandy small path overgrown by bamboo</l>
<l rend="indent2">[and] embraced her bosom lustrous with spots,</l>
<l>mother said: “[have] you [been] thus formerly?”</l>
<l rend="indent2">As one who did not answer to that</l>
<l>she looked at my face distressedly – mother!</l>
<l rend="indent2">[Thinking] “how will she live when [mother] realises”</l>
<l>I pointed out the firebrand of kindled sandal</l>
<l rend="indent2">[and] said “here indeed have they been”.</l>
    </lg>
